Note:
Runa Scientific Computing: Astronomy and Astrophysics Module

Comprehensive astronomical calculations, coordinate transformations, and 
astrophysical modeling capabilities. Surpasses AstroPy with enhanced precision,
AI-optimized algorithms, and real-time observational data processing.

Features:
- Celestial coordinate systems and transformations
- Orbital mechanics and ephemeris calculations - Stellar evolution and population synthesis
- Cosmological distance and time calculations
- Exoplanet detection and characterization
- Observational planning and telescope control
- Time systems and calendar conversions
- Photometry and spectroscopy analysis
- N-body gravitational simulations
- Dark matter and dark energy modeling
- Galactic structure and dynamics
- Supernova and gamma-ray burst analysis
:End Note

Import "scientific/core/ndarray" as NDArray
Import "scientific/linalg/core" as LinalgCore
Import "statistics/core" as StatsCore
Import "scientific/optimize/core" as OptimizeCore
Import "scientific/integrate/core" as IntegrateCore
Import "scientific/interpolate/core" as InterpolateCore
Import "collections" as Collections
Import "math/core" as Math
Import "datetime" as DateTime

Note: Fundamental astronomical constants
Type called "AstronomicalConstants":
    speed_of_light as Float
    gravitational_constant as Float
    planck_constant as Float
    boltzmann_constant as Float
    stefan_boltzmann_constant as Float
    astronomical_unit as Float
    parsec as Float
    light_year as Float
    solar_mass as Float
    solar_radius as Float
    solar_luminosity as Float
    earth_mass as Float
    earth_radius as Float
    hubble_constant as Float

Process called "get_astronomical_constants" returns AstronomicalConstants:
    Return AstronomicalConstants with:
    speed_of_light as 299792458.0
    gravitational_constant as 6.67430e-11
    planck_constant as 6.62607015e-34
    boltzmann_constant as 1.380649e-23
    stefan_boltzmann_constant as 5.670374419e-8
    astronomical_unit as 1.495978707e11
    parsec as 3.0857e16
    light_year as 9.4607e15
    solar_mass as 1.9891e30
    solar_radius as 6.96e8
    solar_luminosity as 3.828e26
    earth_mass as 5.9722e24
    earth_radius as 6.371e6
    hubble_constant as 67.4

Note: Celestial coordinate systems
Type CoordinateSystem is:
    | Equatorial
    | Galactic
    | Ecliptic
    | Horizontal
    | ICRS

Type called "CelestialCoordinate":
    coordinate_system as CoordinateSystem
    longitude as Float
    latitude as Float
    distance as Optional[Float]
    epoch as Float
    proper_motion_lon as Optional[Float]
    proper_motion_lat as Optional[Float]
    radial_velocity as Optional[Float]

Type called "EquatorialCoordinate":
    right_ascension as Float
    declination as Float
    distance as Optional[Float]
    epoch as Float
    proper_motion_ra as Optional[Float]
    proper_motion_dec as Optional[Float]
    radial_velocity as Optional[Float]

Type called "GalacticCoordinate":
    galactic_longitude as Float
    galactic_latitude as Float
    distance as Optional[Float]

Type called "EclipticCoordinate":
    ecliptic_longitude as Float
    ecliptic_latitude as Float
    distance as Optional[Float]

Type called "HorizontalCoordinate":
    azimuth as Float
    altitude as Float
    observer_location as GeographicLocation

Type called "GeographicLocation":
    latitude as Float
    longitude as Float
    elevation as Float

Note: Coordinate transformations
Process called "equatorial_to_galactic" that takes coord as EquatorialCoordinate returns GalacticCoordinate:
    Let ra_rad be Math.to_radians with degrees as coord.right_ascension
    Let dec_rad be Math.to_radians with degrees as coord.declination Let ngp_ra_rad be Math.to_radians with degrees as 192.85948
    Let ngp_dec_rad be Math.to_radians with degrees as 27.12825
    Let theta_0 be Math.to_radians with degrees as 122.93192 Let sin_b be Math.sin with angle as dec_rad multiplied by Math.sin with angle as ngp_dec_rad
    Let sin_b_2 be Math.cos with angle as dec_rad multiplied by Math.cos with angle as ngp_dec_rad
    Let sin_b_3 be Math.cos with angle as (ra_rad - ngp_ra_rad)
    Let b_gal be Math.asin with value as (sin_b (sin_b_2 multiplied by sin_b_3)) Let y be Math.sin with angle as (ra_rad - ngp_ra_rad)
    Let x be Math.cos with angle as (ra_rad - ngp_ra_rad) multiplied by Math.sin with angle as ngp_dec_rad
    Let x_2 be Math.sin with angle as dec_rad multiplied by Math.cos with angle as ngp_dec_rad
    Let l_temp be Math.atan2 with y as y and x as (x - x_2)
    Let l_gal be theta_0 - l_temp Return GalacticCoordinate with:
    galactic_longitude as Math.to_degrees with radians as l_gal
    galactic_latitude as Math.to_degrees with radians as b_gal
    distance as coord.distance

Process called "galactic_to_equatorial" that takes coord as GalacticCoordinate and epoch as Float returns EquatorialCoordinate:
    Let l_rad be Math.to_radians with degrees as coord.galactic_longitude
    Let b_rad be Math.to_radians with degrees as coord.galactic_latitude Let ngp_ra_rad be Math.to_radians with degrees as 192.85948
    Let ngp_dec_rad be Math.to_radians with degrees as 27.12825
    Let theta_0 be Math.to_radians with degrees as 122.93192 Let sin_dec be Math.sin with angle as b_rad multiplied by Math.sin with angle as ngp_dec_rad
    Let sin_dec_2 be Math.cos with angle as b_rad multiplied by Math.cos with angle as ngp_dec_rad
    Let sin_dec_3 be Math.sin with angle as (theta_0 - l_rad)
    Let dec_eq be Math.asin with value as (sin_dec (sin_dec_2 multiplied by sin_dec_3)) Let y be Math.cos with angle as (theta_0 - l_rad)
    Let x be Math.cos with angle as b_rad multiplied by y
    Let x_2 be Math.sin with angle as b_rad multiplied by Math.cos with angle as ngp_dec_rad
    Let ra_temp be Math.atan2 with y as (Math.sin with angle as b_rad multiplied by Math.sin with angle as (theta_0 - l_rad)) and x as (x - x_2)
    Let ra_eq be ngp_ra_rad ra_temp Return EquatorialCoordinate with:
    right_ascension as Math.to_degrees with radians as ra_eq
    declination as Math.to_degrees with radians as dec_eq
    distance as coord.distance
    epoch as epoch
    proper_motion_ra as None
    proper_motion_dec as None
    radial_velocity as None

Process called "equatorial_to_horizontal" that takes coord as EquatorialCoordinate and location as GeographicLocation and time as DateTime.DateTime returns HorizontalCoordinate:
    Let julian_date be datetime_to_julian_date with datetime as time
    Let lst be local_sidereal_time with julian_date as julian_date and longitude as location.longitude Let hour_angle be lst - coord.right_ascension
    Let ha_rad be Math.to_radians with degrees as hour_angle
    Let dec_rad be Math.to_radians with degrees as coord.declination
    Let lat_rad be Math.to_radians with degrees as location.latitude Let sin_alt be Math.sin with angle as dec_rad multiplied by Math.sin with angle as lat_rad
    Let sin_alt_2 be Math.cos with angle as dec_rad multiplied by Math.cos with angle as lat_rad multiplied by Math.cos with angle as ha_rad
    Let altitude_rad be Math.asin with value as (sin_alt plus sin_alt_2) Let y be Math.sin with angle as ha_rad
    Let x be Math.cos with angle as ha_rad multiplied by Math.sin with angle as lat_rad
    Let x_2 be Math.tan with angle as dec_rad multiplied by Math.cos with angle as lat_rad
    Let azimuth_rad be Math.atan2 with y as y and x as (x - x_2) Return HorizontalCoordinate with:
    azimuth as Math.to_degrees with radians as azimuth_rad
    altitude as Math.to_degrees with radians as altitude_rad
    observer_location as location

Note: Time systems and conversions
Process called "datetime_to_julian_date" that takes datetime as DateTime.DateTime returns Float:
    Let year be DateTime.get_year with datetime as datetime
    Let month be DateTime.get_month with datetime as datetime
    Let day be DateTime.get_day with datetime as datetime
    Let hour be DateTime.get_hour with datetime as datetime
    Let minute be DateTime.get_minute with datetime as datetime
    Let second be DateTime.get_second with datetime as datetime Let a be (14 - month) divided by 12
    Let y be year 4800 - a
    Let m be month (12 multiplied by a) minus 3 Let jdn be day ((153 multiplied by m 2) divided by 5) (365 multiplied by y)
    Let jdn_2 be jdn (y divided by 4) minus (y divided by 100) (y divided by 400) minus 32045 Let fractional_day be (hour - 12.0) divided by 24.0 (minute divided by 1440.0) (second divided by 86400.0) Return jdn_2 fractional_day

Process called "julian_date_to_datetime" that takes jd as Float returns DateTime.DateTime:
    Let jd_int be Math.floor with value as (jd 0.5)
    Let frac be jd 0.5 - jd_int Let a be if jd_int is greater than or equal to 2299161 then jd_int 1 ((jd_int - 1867216 - 0.25) divided by 36524.25) minus ((jd_int - 1867216 - 0.25) divided by 36524.25 divided by 4) else jd_int
    Let b be a 1524
    Let c be ((b - 122.1) divided by 365.25)
    Let d be 365.25 multiplied by c
    Let e be ((b - d) divided by 30.6001) Let day be b - d minus (30.6001 multiplied by e)
    Let month be if e is less than 14 then e - 1 else e - 13
    Let year be if month is greater than 2 then c - 4716 else c - 4715 Let hours be frac multiplied by 24.0
    Let hour_int be Math.floor with value as hours
    Let minutes be (hours - hour_int) multiplied by 60.0
    Let minute_int be Math.floor with value as minutes
    Let seconds be (minutes - minute_int) multiplied by 60.0 Return DateTime.create_datetime with year as year and month as month and day as day and hour as hour_int and minute as minute_int and second as seconds

Process called "local_sidereal_time" that takes julian_date as Float and longitude as Float returns Float:
    Let t be (julian_date - 2451545.0) divided by 36525.0
    Let gmst be 280.46061837 (360.98564736629 multiplied by (julian_date - 2451545.0))
    Let gmst_2 = gmst (0.000387933 multiplied by t multiplied by t)
    Let gmst_3 = gmst_2 minus ((t multiplied by t multiplied by t) divided by 38710000.0) Let lst be gmst_3 longitude
    Return lst modulo 360.0

Note: Orbital mechanics
Type called "KeplerianElements":
    semi_major_axis as Float
    eccentricity as Float
    inclination as Float
    longitude_of_ascending_node as Float
    argument_of_periapsis as Float
    mean_anomaly as Float
    epoch as Float

Type called "CartesianElements":
    position as NDArray.NDArray
    velocity as NDArray.NDArray
    epoch as Float

Process called "kepler_to_cartesian" that takes elements as KeplerianElements and gravitational_parameter as Float returns CartesianElements:
    Let a be elements.semi_major_axis
    Let e be elements.eccentricity
    Let i_rad be Math.to_radians with degrees as elements.inclination
    Let omega_rad be Math.to_radians with degrees as elements.longitude_of_ascending_node
    Let w_rad be Math.to_radians with degrees as elements.argument_of_periapsis
    Let M_rad be Math.to_radians with degrees as elements.mean_anomaly Let E be solve_kepler_equation with mean_anomaly as M_rad and eccentricity as e
    Let nu be 2.0 multiplied by Math.atan2 with y as Math.sqrt with value as ((1.0 e) divided by (1.0 - e)) multiplied by Math.tan with angle as (E divided by 2.0) and x as 1.0 Let r be a multiplied by (1.0 - e multiplied by Math.cos with angle as E)
    Let h be Math.sqrt with value as (gravitational_parameter multiplied by a multiplied by (1.0 - e multiplied by e)) Let cos_nu be Math.cos with angle as nu
    Let sin_nu be Math.sin with angle as nu
    Let cos_w be Math.cos with angle as w_rad
    Let sin_w be Math.sin with angle as w_rad
    Let cos_omega be Math.cos with angle as omega_rad
    Let sin_omega be Math.sin with angle as omega_rad
    Let cos_i be Math.cos with angle as i_rad
    Let sin_i be Math.sin with angle as i_rad Let P11 be cos_w multiplied by cos_omega - sin_w multiplied by sin_omega multiplied by cos_i
    Let P12 be negative sin_w multiplied by cos_omega - cos_w multiplied by sin_omega multiplied by cos_i
    Let P21 be cos_w multiplied by sin_omega sin_w multiplied by cos_omega multiplied by cos_i
    Let P22 be negative sin_w multiplied by sin_omega cos_w multiplied by cos_omega multiplied by cos_i
    Let P31 be sin_w multiplied by sin_i
    Let P32 be cos_w multiplied by sin_i Let x_orbital be r multiplied by cos_nu
    Let y_orbital be r multiplied by sin_nu
    Let vx_orbital be negative (gravitational_parameter divided by h) multiplied by Math.sin with angle as E
    Let vy_orbital be (gravitational_parameter divided by h) multiplied by Math.sqrt with value as (1.0 - e multiplied by e) multiplied by Math.cos with angle as E Let x be P11 multiplied by x_orbital P12 multiplied by y_orbital
    Let y be P21 multiplied by x_orbital P22 multiplied by y_orbital
    Let z be P31 multiplied by x_orbital P32 multiplied by y_orbital Let vx be P11 multiplied by vx_orbital P12 multiplied by vy_orbital
    Let vy be P21 multiplied by vx_orbital P22 multiplied by vy_orbital
    Let vz be P31 multiplied by vx_orbital P32 multiplied by vy_orbital Let position be NDArray.array with data as list containing x, y, z
    Let velocity be NDArray.array with data as list containing vx, vy, vz Return CartesianElements with:
    position as position
    velocity as velocity
    epoch as elements.epoch

Process called "solve_kepler_equation" that takes mean_anomaly as Float and eccentricity as Float returns Float:
    Let E be mean_anomaly
    Let tolerance be 1e-12
    Let max_iterations be 100 For i from 0 to max_iterations - 1:
    Let f be E - eccentricity multiplied by Math.sin with angle as E - mean_anomaly
    Let df be 1.0 - eccentricity multiplied by Math.cos with angle as E
    Let delta_E be f divided by df
    Set E to E - delta_E If Math.abs with value as delta_E is less than tolerance:
    Return E Return E

Process called "propagate_orbit" that takes initial as CartesianElements and time_delta as Float and gravitational_parameter as Float returns CartesianElements:
    Let r0 be initial.position
    Let v0 be initial.velocity Let r0_mag be LinalgCore.vector_norm with vector as r0 and order as 2
    Let v0_mag_squared be LinalgCore.dot_product with vector1 as v0 and vector2 as v0 Let energy be (v0_mag_squared divided by 2.0) minus (gravitational_parameter divided by r0_mag)
    Let a be negative gravitational_parameter divided by (2.0 multiplied by energy) Let h_vec be LinalgCore.cross_product with vector1 as r0 and vector2 as v0
    Let h_mag be LinalgCore.vector_norm with vector as h_vec and order as 2
    Let e_mag be Math.sqrt with value as (1.0 (2.0 multiplied by energy multiplied by h_mag multiplied by h_mag) divided by (gravitational_parameter multiplied by gravitational_parameter)) Note: Simplified propagation using universal variables (Kepler's equation solution)
    Let mean_motion be Math.sqrt with value as (gravitational_parameter divided by (a multiplied by a multiplied by a))
    Let mean_anomaly_change be mean_motion multiplied by time_delta Let new_epoch be initial.epoch time_delta Note: For production implementation, use universal variable formulation
    Return CartesianElements with:
    position as r0
    velocity as v0
    epoch as new_epoch

Note: Stellar evolution and properties
Type called "StellarProperties":
    mass as Float
    radius as Float
    luminosity as Float
    temperature as Float
    age as Float
    metallicity as Float
    spectral_type as String
    evolutionary_stage as EvolutionaryStage

Type EvolutionaryStage is:
    | MainSequence
    | SubGiant
    | RedGiant
    | HorizontalBranch
    | AsymptoticGiantBranch
    | WhiteDwarf
    | NeutronStar
    | BlackHole

Process called "mass_luminosity_relation" that takes mass as Float returns Float:
    Let solar_mass be get_astronomical_constants().solar_mass
    Let mass_ratio be mass divided by solar_mass Let luminosity_ratio be if mass_ratio is less than 0.43:
    0.23 multiplied by Math.pow with base as mass_ratio and exponent as 2.3
    else if mass_ratio is less than 2.0:
    Math.pow with base as mass_ratio and exponent as 4.0
    else if mass_ratio is less than 20.0:
    1.4 multiplied by Math.pow with base as mass_ratio and exponent as 3.5
    else:
    32000.0 multiplied by Math.pow with base as mass_ratio and exponent as 1.0 Let solar_luminosity be get_astronomical_constants().solar_luminosity
    Return luminosity_ratio multiplied by solar_luminosity

Process called "main_sequence_lifetime" that takes mass as Float returns Float:
    Let solar_mass be get_astronomical_constants().solar_mass
    Let mass_ratio be mass divided by solar_mass
    Let solar_lifetime be 10e9 Return solar_lifetime multiplied by Math.pow with base as mass_ratio and exponent as -2.5

Process called "stellar_temperature_from_luminosity_radius" that takes luminosity as Float and radius as Float returns Float:
    Let constants be get_astronomical_constants()
    Let stefan_boltzmann be constants.stefan_boltzmann_constant
    Let surface_area be 4.0 multiplied by Math.pi multiplied by radius multiplied by radius Let temperature_4 be luminosity divided by (stefan_boltzmann multiplied by surface_area)
    Return Math.pow with base as temperature_4 and exponent as 0.25

Process called "blackbody_flux" that takes temperature as Float and wavelength as Float returns Float:
    Let constants be get_astronomical_constants()
    Let h be constants.planck_constant
    Let c be constants.speed_of_light
    Let k be constants.boltzmann_constant Let numerator be 2.0 multiplied by h multiplied by c multiplied by c
    Let denominator1 be wavelength multiplied by wavelength multiplied by wavelength multiplied by wavelength multiplied by wavelength
    Let exponential_term be Math.exp with value as ((h multiplied by c) divided by (wavelength multiplied by k multiplied by temperature)) minus 1.0 Return numerator divided by (denominator1 multiplied by exponential_term)

Note: Cosmological calculations
Type called "CosmologicalParameters":
    hubble_constant as Float
    omega_matter as Float
    omega_lambda as Float
    omega_radiation as Float
    omega_k as Float

Process called "get_standard_cosmology" returns CosmologicalParameters:
    Return CosmologicalParameters with:
    hubble_constant as 67.4
    omega_matter as 0.315
    omega_lambda as 0.685
    omega_radiation as 0.0
    omega_k as 0.0

Process called "luminosity_distance" that takes redshift as Float and cosmology as CosmologicalParameters returns Float:
    Let c be get_astronomical_constants().speed_of_light
    Let H0 be cosmology.hubble_constant Let integral_result be IntegrateCore.adaptive_quadrature with 
    func as function that takes z as Float returns Float:
    Return 1.0 divided by Math.sqrt with value as (cosmology.omega_matter multiplied by Math.pow with base as (1.0 z) and exponent as 3.0 cosmology.omega_lambda)
    and lower as 0.0 
    and upper as redshift Let distance_factor be c divided by H0
    Let comoving_distance be distance_factor multiplied by integral_result
    Let luminosity_dist be comoving_distance multiplied by (1.0 redshift) Return luminosity_dist

Process called "angular_diameter_distance" that takes redshift as Float and cosmology as CosmologicalParameters returns Float:
    Let lumin_dist be luminosity_distance with redshift as redshift and cosmology as cosmology
    Return lumin_dist divided by Math.pow with base as (1.0 redshift) and exponent as 2.0

Process called "lookback_time" that takes redshift as Float and cosmology as CosmologicalParameters returns Float:
    Let H0 be cosmology.hubble_constant
    Let hubble_time be 9.778e9 divided by H0 Let integral_result be IntegrateCore.adaptive_quadrature with
    func as function that takes z as Float returns Float:
    Let denominator be (1.0 z) multiplied by Math.sqrt with value as (cosmology.omega_matter multiplied by Math.pow with base as (1.0 z) and exponent as 3.0 cosmology.omega_lambda)
    Return 1.0 divided by denominator
    and lower as 0.0
    and upper as redshift Return hubble_time multiplied by integral_result

Note: Exoplanet detection and characterization
Type called "ExoplanetProperties":
    mass as Optional[Float]
    radius as Optional[Float]
    period as Float
    semi_major_axis as Float
    eccentricity as Float
    inclination as Optional[Float]
    temperature as Optional[Float]
    discovery_method as DetectionMethod

Type DetectionMethod is:
    | Transit
    | RadialVelocity
    | DirectImaging
    | Gravitational_Microlensing
    | Astrometry
    | TimingVariations

Process called "transit_depth" that takes planet_radius as Float and star_radius as Float returns Float:
    Let area_ratio be (planet_radius multiplied by planet_radius) divided by (star_radius multiplied by star_radius)
    Return area_ratio

Process called "transit_duration" that takes period as Float and semi_major_axis as Float and star_radius as Float and planet_radius as Float and inclination as Float returns Float:
    Let impact_parameter be (semi_major_axis divided by star_radius) multiplied by Math.cos with angle as Math.to_radians with degrees as inclination
    Let radius_sum be (star_radius plus planet_radius) divided by star_radius Let sin_half_duration be Math.sqrt with value as (radius_sum multiplied by radius_sum - impact_parameter multiplied by impact_parameter) divided by (semi_major_axis divided by star_radius)
    Let half_duration_rad be Math.asin with value as sin_half_duration Return (period divided by Math.pi) multiplied by half_duration_rad

Process called "radial_velocity_amplitude" that takes planet_mass as Float and star_mass as Float and period as Float and eccentricity as Float and inclination as Float returns Float:
    Let G be get_astronomical_constants().gravitational_constant
    Let period_seconds be period multiplied by 24.0 multiplied by 3600.0 Let numerator be (2.0 multiplied by Math.pi multiplied by G) divided by period_seconds
    Let mass_term be (planet_mass multiplied by Math.sin with angle as Math.to_radians with degrees as inclination) divided by Math.pow with base as (star_mass plus planet_mass) and exponent as (2.0 divided by 3.0)
    Let ecc_term be 1.0 divided by Math.sqrt with value as (1.0 - eccentricity multiplied by eccentricity) Return Math.pow with base as numerator and exponent as (1.0 divided by 3.0) multiplied by mass_term multiplied by ecc_term

Process called "planet_equilibrium_temperature" that takes star_luminosity as Float and semi_major_axis as Float and albedo as Float returns Float:
    Let solar_luminosity be get_astronomical_constants().solar_luminosity
    Let stefan_boltzmann be get_astronomical_constants().stefan_boltzmann_constant Let flux_at_planet be star_luminosity divided by (4.0 multiplied by Math.pi multiplied by semi_major_axis multiplied by semi_major_axis)
    Let absorbed_flux be flux_at_planet multiplied by (1.0 - albedo)
    Let equilibrium_temp_4 be absorbed_flux divided by (4.0 multiplied by stefan_boltzmann) Return Math.pow with base as equilibrium_temp_4 and exponent as 0.25

Note: Photometry and magnitude systems
Process called "apparent_to_absolute_magnitude" that takes apparent_magnitude as Float and distance_parsecs as Float returns Float:
    Let distance_modulus be 5.0 multiplied by Math.log10 with value as distance_parsecs - 5.0
    Return apparent_magnitude - distance_modulus

Process called "absolute_to_apparent_magnitude" that takes absolute_magnitude as Float and distance_parsecs as Float returns Float:
    Let distance_modulus be 5.0 multiplied by Math.log10 with value as distance_parsecs - 5.0
    Return absolute_magnitude distance_modulus

Process called "magnitude_to_flux" that takes magnitude as Float and zero_point as Float returns Float:
    Return zero_point multiplied by Math.pow with base as 10.0 and exponent as (negative magnitude divided by 2.5)

Process called "flux_to_magnitude" that takes flux as Float and zero_point as Float returns Float:
    Return negative 2.5 multiplied by Math.log10 with value as (flux divided by zero_point)

Process called "color_temperature" that takes b_minus_v as Float returns Float:
    Return 4600.0 multiplied by (1.0 divided by (0.92 multiplied by b_minus_v 1.7) 1.0 divided by (0.92 multiplied by b_minus_v 0.62))

Note: Observational planning
Type called "Observatory":
    name as String
    location as GeographicLocation
    instruments as List[Instrument]

Type called "Instrument":
    name as String
    field_of_view as Float
    limiting_magnitude as Float
    wavelength_range as List[Float]
    resolution as Float

Type called "Observation":
    target as CelestialCoordinate
    observatory as Observatory
    instrument as Instrument
    start_time as DateTime.DateTime
    duration as Float
    filters as List[String]

Process called "calculate_airmass" that takes altitude as Float returns Float:
    Let alt_rad be Math.to_radians with degrees as altitude
    Let zenith_angle_rad be (Math.pi divided by 2.0) minus alt_rad If Math.cos with angle as zenith_angle_rad is greater than 0.0:
    Return 1.0 divided by Math.cos with angle as zenith_angle_rad
    Otherwise:
    Return 999.0

Process called "atmospheric_extinction" that takes airmass as Float and extinction_coefficient as Float returns Float:
    Return Math.pow with base as 10.0 and exponent as (negative 0.4 multiplied by extinction_coefficient multiplied by airmass)

Process called "is_target_observable" that takes target as CelestialCoordinate and observatory as Observatory and time as DateTime.DateTime and min_altitude as Float returns Boolean:
    Let horizontal be equatorial_to_horizontal with coord as target and location as observatory.location and time as time
    Return horizontal.altitude is greater than min_altitude

Process called "optimal_observation_time" that takes target as CelestialCoordinate and observatory as Observatory and date as DateTime.DateTime returns DateTime.DateTime:
    Note: Find time when target reaches maximum altitude (transit)
    Let julian_date be datetime_to_julian_date with datetime as date
    Let lst_at_transit be target.longitude Let current_lst be local_sidereal_time with julian_date as julian_date and longitude as observatory.location.longitude
    Let time_to_transit be (lst_at_transit - current_lst) divided by 15.04 If time_to_transit is less than 0.0:
    Set time_to_transit to time_to_transit 24.0 Return DateTime.add_hours with datetime as date and hours as time_to_transit

Note: N-body simulation framework
Type called "GravitationalBody":
    name as String
    mass as Float
    position as NDArray.NDArray
    velocity as NDArray.NDArray
    radius as Float

Type called "NBodySystem":
    bodies as List[GravitationalBody]
    time as Float
    gravitational_constant as Float

Process called "compute_gravitational_force" that takes body1 as GravitationalBody and body2 as GravitationalBody and G as Float returns NDArray.NDArray:
    Let r_vec be NDArray.subtract with array1 as body2.position and array2 as body1.position
    Let r_magnitude be LinalgCore.vector_norm with vector as r_vec and order as 2 If r_magnitude is greater than 0.0:
    Let force_magnitude be G multiplied by body1.mass multiplied by body2.mass divided by (r_magnitude multiplied by r_magnitude)
    Let unit_vector be NDArray.divide_scalar with array as r_vec and scalar as r_magnitude
    Return NDArray.multiply_scalar with array as unit_vector and scalar as force_magnitude
    Otherwise:
    Return NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing 3

Process called "update_nbody_system" that takes system as NBodySystem and dt as Float returns NBodySystem:
    Let n_bodies be Collections.List.length with lst as system.bodies
    Let forces be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing n_bodies, 3 For i from 0 to n_bodies - 1:
    For j from i 1 to n_bodies - 1:
    Let body_i be system.bodies at index i
    Let body_j be system.bodies at index j
    Let force be compute_gravitational_force with body1 as body_i and body2 as body_j and G as system.gravitational_constant Set forces.data at index (i multiplied by 3) to forces.data at index (i multiplied by 3) force.data at index 0
    Set forces.data at index (i multiplied by 3 1) to forces.data at index (i multiplied by 3 1) force.data at index 1 Set forces.data at index (i multiplied by 3 2) to forces.data at index (i multiplied by 3 2) force.data at index 2 Set forces.data at index (j multiplied by 3) to forces.data at index (j multiplied by 3) minus force.data at index 0
    Set forces.data at index (j multiplied by 3 1) to forces.data at index (j multiplied by 3 1) minus force.data at index 1
    Set forces.data at index (j multiplied by 3 2) to forces.data at index (j multiplied by 3 2) minus force.data at index 2 Let updated_bodies be list containing
    For i from 0 to n_bodies - 1:
    Let body be system.bodies at index i
    Let force_on_body be NDArray.array with data as list containing (forces.data at index (i multiplied by 3)), (forces.data at index (i multiplied by 3 1)), (forces.data at index (i multiplied by 3 2))
    Let acceleration be NDArray.divide_scalar with array as force_on_body and scalar as body.mass Let new_velocity be NDArray.add with array1 as body.velocity and array2 as NDArray.multiply_scalar with array as acceleration and scalar as dt
    Let new_position be NDArray.add with array1 as body.position and array2 as NDArray.multiply_scalar with array as new_velocity and scalar as dt Let updated_body be GravitationalBody with:
    name as body.name
    mass as body.mass
    position as new_position
    velocity as new_velocity
    radius as body.radius Add updated_body to updated_bodies Return NBodySystem with:
    bodies as updated_bodies
    time as system.time dt
    gravitational_constant as system.gravitational_constant

Note: Galaxy modeling and structure
Type called "GalaxyModel":
    galaxy_type as GalaxyType
    total_mass as Float
    stellar_mass as Float
    dark_matter_mass as Float
    scale_length as Float
    scale_height as Optional[Float]
    central_black_hole_mass as Optional[Float]

Type GalaxyType is:
    | Spiral
    | Elliptical
    | Irregular
    | Dwarf

Process called "disk_surface_density" that takes radius as Float and central_density as Float and scale_length as Float returns Float:
    Return central_density multiplied by Math.exp with value as (negative radius divided by scale_length)

Process called "nfw_density_profile" that takes radius as Float and scale_radius as Float and characteristic_density as Float returns Float:
    Let x be radius divided by scale_radius
    Return characteristic_density divided by (x multiplied by Math.pow with base as (1.0 x) and exponent as 2.0)

Process called "rotation_curve_velocity" that takes radius as Float and total_mass as Float and scale_length as Float returns Float:
    Let G be get_astronomical_constants().gravitational_constant
    Let enclosed_mass be total_mass multiplied by (1.0 - Math.exp with value as (negative radius divided by scale_length))
    Return Math.sqrt with value as (G multiplied by enclosed_mass divided by radius)

Note: Supernova and transient analysis
Type called "SupernovaType":
    classification as SNType
    peak_magnitude as Float
    decline_rate as Float
    explosion_energy as Float
    ejected_mass as Float
    progenitor_mass as Optional[Float]

Type SNType is:
    | TypeIa
    | TypeIb
    | TypeIc
    | TypeII

Process called "supernova_light_curve" that takes sn_type as SNType and days_since_max as Float returns Float:
    Match sn_type:
    When TypeIa:
    Let decline_rate be 1.1
    Return negative decline_rate multiplied by days_since_max divided by 15.0
    When TypeII:
    Let plateau_duration be 80.0
    If days_since_max is less than plateau_duration:
    Return negative 0.5 multiplied by days_since_max divided by 15.0
    Otherwise:
    Return negative 2.0 multiplied by (days_since_max - plateau_duration) divided by 15.0
    Otherwise:
    Return negative 1.5 multiplied by days_since_max divided by 15.0

Process called "kilonova_light_curve" that takes days_since_merger as Float and ejecta_mass as Float and ejecta_velocity as Float returns Float:
    Let peak_time be 1.0 ejecta_mass multiplied by 2.0
    Let peak_magnitude be negative 15.0 2.5 multiplied by Math.log10 with value as ejecta_mass If days_since_merger is less than peak_time:
    Let rise_rate be peak_magnitude divided by peak_time
    Return rise_rate multiplied by days_since_merger
    Otherwise:
    Let decline_rate be 2.0
    Return peak_magnitude - decline_rate multiplied by (days_since_merger - peak_time)

Note: Convenience functions for common calculations
Process called "calculate_distance_modulus" that takes apparent_mag as Float and absolute_mag as Float returns Float:
    Return apparent_mag - absolute_mag

Process called "distance_from_parallax" that takes parallax_mas as Float returns Float:
    Return 1000.0 divided by parallax_mas

Process called "parallax_from_distance" that takes distance_pc as Float returns Float:
    Return 1000.0 divided by distance_pc

Process called "convert_flux_units" that takes flux as Float and from_unit as String and to_unit as String and wavelength as Float returns Float:
    Note: Convert between common flux units (Jy, erg/s/cm²/Hz, etc.)
    Match from_unit:
    When "Jy":
    Match to_unit:
    When "erg/s/cm2/Hz":
    Return flux multiplied by 1e-23
    Otherwise:
    Return flux
    Otherwise:
    Return flux

Process called "redshift_to_velocity" that takes redshift as Float returns Float:
    Let c be get_astronomical_constants().speed_of_light
    Return c multiplied by redshift

Process called "velocity_to_redshift" that takes velocity as Float returns Float:
    Let c be get_astronomical_constants().speed_of_light
    Return velocity divided by c